Checkpoint — Answer These Before We Move On
Three questions, plain English, no code:
1. What's the difference between two pointers and sliding window?
    Two pointers — one at each end, move inward toward each other. Works on sorted data because 
    sorting gives you a rule: too big → move right, too small → move left.
   sliding window — both pointers at the left, move in the same direction. 
   Works on any data because you're just maintaining a window of consecutive elements.

2. Why does two pointers only work on a sorted list for the two sum problem?
    Right instinct, wrong explanation. The real reason is: with an unsorted list you have 
    no rule to decide which pointer to move. If the sum is too big,
     you don't know whether moving left or right will fix it — because bigger numbers
      could be anywhere. The sorted order is what gives you the decision rule.

3.  In your sliding window solution, what does nums[i - k] represent?
 Exactly right. When your window is at position i, the element that just left the window is at i - k. 
 You subtract it to slide the window forward without recalculating everything.

